{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489285"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:11:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:11:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"627"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/627"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.21,0.08,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103081"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/627"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85545"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"100"},{"type":"tags","id":"489"},{"type":"tags","id":"2100"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36445"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103081"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to hospital for a dilatation and curettage. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never used oral contraceptives. She has never smoked and does not drink alcohol. There is no personal or family history of venous thromboembolism. She exercises regularly. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 22 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. The planned procedure is expected to take 20 minutes under general anaesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate venous thromboembolism prophylaxis in addition to compression stockings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No additional prophylaxis","Enoxaparin until discharge","Enoxaparin for seven days","Aspirin until discharge","Aspirin for seven days"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is undergoing a minor gynaecological procedure and has minimal risk factors for venous thromboembolism (VTE). A commonly used risk assessment tool for general surgical patients is the Caprini thrombosis risk model which takes into account age, surgery type, medical history, and history of VTE as well as clinical evidence of peripheral venous disease. Interpretation of the Caprini model is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVery low risk (\u0026lt;0.5%): 0 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELow risk (1.5%): 1-2 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EModerate risk (3%): 3-4 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHigh risk (\u0026gt;6%): \u0026gt;5 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk assessment using the Caprini score helps determine the need for VTE prophylaxis. This patient scores only 1 point (for surgery), placing her in the very low-risk category. \u003Cstrong\u003ENo additional prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E beyond mechanical methods is appropriate for low-risk patients (Caprini score \u22642) undergoing minor procedures. Early mobilisation and mechanical prophylaxis with compression stockings are sufficient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin until discharge\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for this low-risk patient. Low molecular weight heparin prophylaxis is typically reserved for patients with moderate to high risk of VTE (Caprini score \u0026gt;2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin for seven days\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for high-risk patients (Caprini score \u22655) but is not warranted in this case given the patient\u0027s low risk profile and minor procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin until discharge\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as primary VTE prophylaxis in surgical patients as it provides inadequate protection compared to low molecular weight heparin when prophylaxis is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin for seven days\u003C/strong\u003E is similarly not appropriate as it is not an evidence-based strategy for perioperative VTE prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Caprini score is the best-validated risk assessment tool for perioperative DVT risk assessment.","Patients at low risk of DVT (Caprini score \u22642) undergoing minor procedures do not require DVT chemoprophylaxis.","Mechanical prophylaxis with compression stockings is appropriate for all surgical patients regardless of risk."],"references":["Pannucci CJ, Swistun L, MacDonald JK, Henke PK, Brooke BS. Individualized Venous Thromboembolism Risk Stratification Using the 2005 Caprini Score to Identify the Benefits and Harms of Chemoprophylaxis in Surgical Patients: A Meta-analysis. Ann Surg. 2017 Jun;265(6):1094-1103. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28106607/","Guideline for the Prevention of Venous Thromboembolism (VTE) in Adult Hospitalised Patients. In: QLD Health [online]. Available at: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0031/812938/vte-prevention-guideline.pdf","Caprini JA. Risk assessment as a guide for the prevention of the many faces of venous thromboembolism. Am J Surg 2010, 199: S3\u2013S10.","Wilson S, Chen X, Cronin M, et al. Thrombosis prophylaxis in surgical patients using the Caprini Risk Score. Cur Prob Surg 2022; 59; 101221"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85545"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"627"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85545"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-19T09:01:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-19T09:04:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"627"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103081"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"re